    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-19T14:41:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-19T14:41:00-05:00" n="453"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d453">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 656.119/139</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Garrett</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-19T20:00:00+00:19">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 19, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received January 20, 8 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1906. Referring to my 1899, January 17, 8 p.m. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> tells me that recently
                    the German Minister told him that the German <pb facs="0558" n="1392"
                        xml:id="pg_1392"/> prize-court regulation not hitherto applied to Dutch
                    ships would be so applied on and after the 13th instant. The German Minister in
                    the same conversation said that he was sure no objection would be taken to the
                        <hi rend="italic">Nieuw Amsterdam</hi> on her outward trip if assurances
                    were given that would not be detained at New York. <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LJJ1">Loudon</persName> therefore cabled you
                    but left out the reasons, fearing that you would consider it a threat and
                    therefore difficult to accede to. He did not wish me to cable you as above, but
                    I told him I felt sure you would not take it in that sense and that it was
                    better that you should know the reason the <hi rend="italic">Nieuw
                        Amsterdam</hi> has not yet sailed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Garrett</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
